1.1. At least 10 000 youth (disaggregated by gender) covered by jobs fairs conducted in line with new Standard Operating Procedures (SOP)
1.2. a) Availability of mobile application for vacancy posting and job application targeted on rural youth, and b) annual 10% increase of application users (disaggregated by gender);
1.3. At least 1 000 youth (disaggregated by gender) trained using enhanced training materials on soft and professional skills (30/70 ratio) at Centers of Professional Development in target regions
2.1. 12 start-ups supported with a special focus on youth and women.
3.1. Availability of methodology and guidelines on gathering gender disaggregated data for measuring youth unemployment rates in line with international standards;
3.2. 1 000 staff-members (disaggregated by gender) improved their knowledge on active labour market policy.

1.1. The TOR and draft SOP for organizing mobile job fairs have been developed, the organization of mobile job fairs in pilot regions planned in the next reporting period (pending on printing guideline on soft skills and procurement of equipment recommended for situational rooms);
1.2. The project developed TOR to develop a mobile application for “Unified National Labor System”, based on announced RFP bids selected and contracted a local company. In order to assist the Government and MELR in digitalization of employment services the project supported developing the MyMehnat (“my labour”) mobile application aimed at improving access of youth to job vacancies, creating CVs and job applications. Trainings conducted to 26 MELR and employment service specialists (10 of which are women) on administering and using the mobile application. 
The project also assisted developing TOR for mobile application “Labor Migration” to digitalize public services on migration.
1.3. Draft of guidebook with training materials on improving universal (“soft”) and professional skills of young people is developed based on international best experience on a) self-management, b) drawing up a resume, c) passing job interview, d) effective communication and teamwork and e) understanding labor law. Series of training modules developed and planned to be conducted at Centers of Professional Development in target regions in the next reporting period;
2.1. In order to support youth business and startup projects several initiatives were implemented, including following:
a) The 5-cycle of youth support program Startup Initiatives is implemented with 905 applications, 247 startup projects selected, of which 59 headed by girls (22%), representing over 750 team members, of which 249 girls (29%) to participate in online intensive trainings, including 13 topics with over 650 slides, and mentorship support by 12 qualified experts. 176 project teams attempted to implement the projects on the Accelerator.uz platform, researching needs of target customers, developing minimum viable products, and testing first sales. 92 projects reached the final of the acceleration program, presented their startups to experts, and 40 best startups across the country (10 headed by girls) provided seed grants by 50 million UZS ($5,000) co-funded by “Yoshlar Kelajagimiz” foundation;
b) Under Small Business Support project 34 small business and individual labor initiatives from 6 target regions (Andijan, Namangan, Jizzakh, Navoi, Kashkadarya and Surkhandarya) were supported by providing complex training and 323 pieces of equipment (sewing machines, IT equipment and furniture) worth $127,500 to launch and expand businesses activities, creating 187 jobs (132 of which are women) and improving job and income opportunities to 159 youth and women.
c) Under Integrated Business Support project 94 small businesses (of which 20 are headed by women) from 5 target regions (Namangan, Fergana, Jizzakh, Samarkand and Kashkadarya) trained on 4-week trainings on business management, marketing, finance and soft skills. 43 projects (of which 12 are led by women) received over $466,000 worth of production equipment to start and expand their business activities, thus creating 330 new jobs for youth, of which 99 for women, and improving vocational and entrepreneurial skills, employment and income opportunities for 170 youth, of which 51 for young women; 
d) Under “Business Clinic” project over 5,393 business entities provided instant consultations on Covid-19 related support measures by the government, over 3,300 business entities participated in 83 webinars, over 350 infographics were posted on social networks with excerpts from government support measures, and under Q&A and ‘Do you know’ headlines, 67 video answers to most critical questions uploaded on Youtube;
3.1. Methodology and guidelines for data collection for measuring youth unemployment by gender have been developed and submitted to national counterparts in MELR. The project also developed analytical report with methodology on organizing Republican Competition and Social Responsibility and Efficiency rating system. 15 representatives of MELR and other partners were trained on procedures, data analysis and methodology of applying rating system for assessment of participants.
The project supported National Association for the Development and Popularization of Working Professions (WorldSkills Uzbekistan - WSU) and Monocenter Ishga Marhamat to develop capacity and establish Competence Assessment Center and the Center for Professional Education per WorldSkills standards. “WorldSkills Russia” was contracted to train 90 local experts on 14 competencies, and asses their competence in accordance with WorldSkills standards and award WSU Expert certificate. The experts then conducted assessment of 169 graduates of the Monocenter trainings (including 58 women) - at least 10 people in each of 14 competencies and awarded internationally recognized certificate of competency - Skills Passports to successful candidates. 
Jointly with UNDP “Covid-19 RR” project, Competence Assessment Centers on 6 professions (IT Software solutions for business; Fashion Technology; Restaurant service; Electrical installation; Painting and decorative work; Aesthetic cosmetology) were provided relevant equipment to conduct trainings and assessment of competence of graduates. The project also helped to improve and print training manuals on 9 competencies and registry book (in 300 quantity each) in accordance with WorldSkills standards disseminated to all 15 provincial monocenters in Uzbekistan. 
3.2. Project conducted training to key personnel of MELR and its regional departments on strategies and practical measures of effective employment promotion policies and programs, which was attended by 70 people (45% of which are women). The project also assisted in translating the Law on Employment and printing 1,500 copies in the form of reference books and 100 copies in the form of gift books. Server and multimedia equipment were provided to monocenter to develop an online learning platform, produce media products and methodological materials for distribution to 15 provincial monocenters.

1.1. At least 5000 of youth (disaggregated by gender) covered by jobs fairs conducted in line with new Standard Operating Procedures (SOP);
1.2. a) Mobile application for vacancy posting and job application targeted on rural youth developed and b) annual 10% increase of application users (disaggregated by gender);
1.3. At least 700 of youth (disaggregated by gender) trained using enhanced training materials on soft and professional skills (30/70 ratio) at Centers of Professional Development in target regions.
2.1. 8 start-ups supported with a special focus on youth and women.
3.1. methodology and guidelines on gathering gender disaggregated data for measuring youth unemployment rates in line with international standards;
3.2. 700 staff-members (disaggregated by gender) improved their knowledge on active labour market policy.

